<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Women’s Aid (JRR 0006)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><a name="OLE_LINK3"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Women's Aid is the national domestic violence charity that supports a network of around 300 local services working to end domestic violence against women and children in England. Our member services are integrated domestic violence service providers delive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ring a range of holistic services for women experiencing domestic violence and their children. Keeping the voices of survivors at the heart of its work, Women's Aid campaigns for better support for women and children, provides training and resources for pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ofessionals and delivers a package of vital 24 hour lifeline services through publications, websites and the National Domestic Violence Helpline (run in partnership with Refuge). </span></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">During 2011/12 Women’s Aid member services provided an estimated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">158,610 wo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">men </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">38,585 children and young people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with direct support following domestic and/or sexual violence. This includes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">19,510 women </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">19,440 children </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">being provided with refuge accommodation, and the remainder with other forms of outreach, advocacy, couns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">elling and support.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Women’s Aid welcomes the opportunity to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">submit evidence to the Joint Committee on Human Rights </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Inquiry into the implications for access to justice of the Government’s proposals to reform judicial review </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and will restrict our comments to our areas of expertise. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Women’s Aid is currently supporting a Judicial Review through the provision of witness statements. We have also considered intervening in Judicial Reviews in the past and strongly believe that Jud</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">icial Review is a crucial legal tool enabling vulnerable groups of people, such as women experiencing domestic violence, to have their voices heard.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We recognise that the Government wants the proposals to act as a disincentive to the bringing of Judicial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reviews because, “the use of judicial review has expanded massively in recent years and it is open to abuse</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.” Howeve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">although there has been an increase in the number of applications for Judicial Review for immigration and asylum cases, the number of ap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plications in criminal cases was virtually static between 2007 and 2012, and there has been a negligible increase in the number of applications for permission for Judicial Review in civil cases.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We also recognise that the Government is concerned, “about t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he time and money wasted in dealing with unmeritorious cases which may be brought simply to generate publicity or to delay implementation of a decision that was properly made</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.” However, we do not believe that the evidence supports the claim that Judicial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reviews are being misused by campaigning groups for publicity purposes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Excluding immigration, asylum and planning cases (as they are to be dealt with by alternative Tribunals), there were approximately 2,300 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Judicial Reviews </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">brought in 2011. Of these, aro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">und 50 were brought by charities, representing only 2% of all non-immigration, asylum and planning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Judicial Reviews</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and 0.4% of all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Judicial Reviews</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Furthermore, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Judicial Reviews </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">brought by charities are disproportionately successful, disproving any asse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rtion that they are misusing Judicial Review as a means of generating headlines or publicity.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Standing for Judicial Reviews</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Women’s Aid believes that the proposed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reform to standing for Judicial Reviews misunderstands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the purpose </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of Judicial Reviews. They</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should be used to address matters of public interest and therefore any change to standing to require a ‘direct and tangible interest’ would alter their purpose to a more private focus.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a charity whose member services worked with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an estimated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">158,610 w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">omen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">38,585 children and young people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in 2011/12, Women’s Aid strongly believes that Judicial Review should remain an option for us seeking to address matters of public interest that impact on women experiencing domestic violence and their children.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">omen’s Aid strongly believe that the proposed reforms to standing should not go forward as they would disproportionality impact on organisations bringing Judicial Reviews on vitally important matters of public interest where individuals have been disempowe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">red to do so on their own behalf. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Third party involvement</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposal to discourage organisations from intervening in cases by imposing additional cost burdens on interveners also suggests a failure to recognise the public focus of judicial review. Where there are important matters of public policy. Intervening </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">organisations, such as Women’s Aid, bring expertise which assists the court’s consideration of the matter. They also draw attention to the wider implications of a decision and expedite the judge’s decision-making on those issues. The creation of additional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cost risks for intervening organisations would discourage their participation in proceedings and reduce the quality of the judgments that result from important Judicial Reviews. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As mentioned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the introduction Women’s Aid has considered intervening in J</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">udicial Reviews before and believes that the option should remain open to us, and other charities, in the future. Any changes to the paying of legal costs for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">intervening organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which creates uncertainty for the costs that charities could incur woul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d create a disincentive for these interventions. We believe that interventions from charities add expertise and experience to Judicial Reviews and these changes would exclude our expertise and voices of women experiencing domestic violence from these impor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tant proceedings. We strongly believe that proposals to reform how costs of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">intervening organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are met in Judicial Reviews are not taken forward.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Women’s Aid greatly values the current Judicial Review system in enabling the voices of women experiencing domestic violence to be heard in cases of public interest. We don’t believe that the evidence shows a “massive” increase in Judicial Reviews being ta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ken by charities or that charities are using Judicial Reviews purely for publicity purposes. We strongly assert that any changes to standing for Judicial Reviews or costs of interveners will impact on charities representing the most vulnerable in society a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd will cut off their voices from being heard. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Ministry of Justice (2013) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Judicial Review: proposals for further reform.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Ibid.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p></body></html>